## Accessibility Best Practices

Building accessible applications requires more than just implementing the technical requirements—it demands thoughtful design and consistent attention to user experience. Here are the essential best practices for creating accessible .NET MAUI Linux applications.

## 1. Design for Accessibility from the Start

Accessibility should be a core requirement, not an afterthought.

**Do:**
```csharp
public class LoginPage : ContentPage
{
    public LoginPage()
    {
        // Accessibility considered from the beginning
        Content = new VerticalStackLayout
        {
            Children =
            {
                new Label 
                { 
                    Text = "Email",
                    SemanticProperties.HeadingLevel = SemanticHeadingLevel.Level1
                },
                new Entry 
                { 
                    Placeholder = "Enter email",
                    Keyboard = Keyboard.Email,
                    AutomationId = "EmailEntry",
                    SemanticProperties.Description = "Your email address"
                },
                new Label { Text = "Password" },
                new Entry 
                { 
                    IsPassword = true,
                    Placeholder = "Enter password",
                    AutomationId = "PasswordEntry"
                },
                new Button 
                { 
                    Text = "Sign In",
                    Command = new Command(SignIn),
                    SemanticProperties.Hint = "Sign in to your account"
                }
            }
        };
    }
}
```

**Don't:**
```csharp
// Missing labels, no semantic information
Content = new VerticalStackLayout
{
    Children =
    {
        new Entry { Placeholder = "Email" },
        new Entry { IsPassword = true },
        new Button { Text = "Go" }
    }
};
```

## 2. Provide Meaningful Labels and Descriptions

Every interactive element must have a clear, descriptive label.

**Good Examples:**

```csharp
// Icon button with descriptive label
var deleteButton = new ImageButton
{
    Source = "trash.png",
    SemanticProperties.Description = "Delete selected message"
};

// Entry with context
var searchEntry = new Entry
{
    Placeholder = "Search contacts",
    SemanticProperties.Description = "Search by name, email, or phone number"
};

// Checkbox with clear purpose
var termsCheckbox = new CheckBox
{
    SemanticProperties.Description = "I agree to the terms and conditions"
};
```

**Avoid:**
- Generic labels: "Button", "Click here", "OK"
- Technical jargon: "Execute query", "Instantiate object"
- Ambiguous icons without text alternatives

## 3. Maintain Logical Focus Order

Tab order should follow visual layout and logical workflow.

```csharp
public class CheckoutForm : ContentPage
{
    public CheckoutForm()
    {
        // Natural top-to-bottom, left-to-right flow
        Content = new VerticalStackLayout
        {
            Children =
            {
                // 1. Shipping information
                new Label { Text = "Shipping Address" },
                new Entry { Placeholder = "Street Address", TabIndex = 0 },
                new Entry { Placeholder = "City", TabIndex = 1 },
                new Entry { Placeholder = "Postal Code", TabIndex = 2 },

                // 2. Payment information
                new Label { Text = "Payment" },
                new Entry { Placeholder = "Card Number", TabIndex = 3 },
                new Entry { Placeholder = "Expiry Date", TabIndex = 4 },
                new Entry { Placeholder = "CVV", TabIndex = 5 },

                // 3. Action buttons
                new HorizontalStackLayout
                {
                    Children =
                    {
                        new Button { Text = "Cancel", TabIndex = 6 },
                        new Button { Text = "Place Order", TabIndex = 7 }
                    }
                }
            }
        };
    }
}
```

## 4. Provide Clear Visual Focus Indicators

Users must always know which element has focus.

```csharp
protected override void OnPaint(SKCanvas canvas)
{
    // Draw control
    DrawControlContent(canvas);

    // Always draw visible focus indicator
    if (IsFocused)
    {
        var focusRect = Bounds;
        focusRect.Inflate(-2, -2);

        using var focusPaint = new SKPaint
        {
            Style = SKPaintStyle.Stroke,
            Color = SkiaTheme.Current.FocusColor,
            StrokeWidth = 2,
            IsAntialias = true
        };

        // High contrast mode: use solid line
        if (SkiaTheme.Current.IsHighContrast)
        {
            canvas.DrawRect(focusRect, focusPaint);
        }
        // Normal mode: use dashed line
        else
        {
            focusPaint.PathEffect = SKPathEffect.CreateDash(new[] { 4f, 2f }, 0);
            canvas.DrawRect(focusRect, focusPaint);
        }
    }
}
```

## 5. Ensure Sufficient Color Contrast

All text must meet WCAG contrast requirements.

```csharp
public class AccessibleLabel : SkiaLabel
{
    protected override void OnPaint(SKCanvas canvas)
    {
        var theme = SkiaTheme.Current;
        var backgroundColor = Parent?.BackgroundColor ?? theme.BackgroundColor;
        var foregroundColor = TextColor ?? theme.ForegroundColor;

        // Check contrast ratio
        var contrastRatio = ContrastChecker.CalculateContrastRatio(
            foregroundColor, 
            backgroundColor);

        // Adjust if insufficient
        if (contrastRatio < theme.MinimumContrastRatio)
        {
            foregroundColor = theme.IsHighContrast
                ? theme.ForegroundColor
                : AdjustColorForContrast(foregroundColor, backgroundColor);
        }

        // Draw with adjusted color
        using var paint = new SKPaint
        {
            Color = foregroundColor,
            TextSize = FontSize,
            IsAntialias = true
        };

        canvas.DrawText(Text, X, Y, paint);
    }
}
```

## 6. Don't Rely on Color Alone

Use multiple visual cues to convey information.

**Good:**
```csharp
public class ValidationEntry : Entry
{
    private bool _isValid = true;

    public bool IsValid
    {
        get => _isValid;
        set
        {
            _isValid = value;

            // Multiple indicators:
            // 1. Border color
            BorderColor = _isValid ? Colors.Gray : Colors.Red;

            // 2. Icon
            var icon = _isValid ? "checkmark.png" : "error.png";

            // 3. Text message
            var message = _isValid 
                ? "Valid input" 
                : "Invalid input: Email format required";

            // 4. Accessible announcement
            SemanticScreenReader.Announce(message);
        }
    }
}
```

**Bad:**
```csharp
// Only color changes, no other indication
entry.BackgroundColor = isValid ? Colors.White : Colors.LightPink;
```

## 7. Provide Text Alternatives for Images

All images must have meaningful text alternatives.

```csharp
// Informative image
var productImage = new Image
{
    Source = "laptop.jpg",
    SemanticProperties.Description = "Silver laptop with 15-inch display"
};

// Decorative image (empty description)
var decorativeBorder = new Image
{
    Source = "border.png",
    SemanticProperties.Description = string.Empty // Indicates decorative
};

// Functional image button
var saveButton = new ImageButton
{
    Source = "save.png",
    SemanticProperties.Description = "Save document"
};
```

## 8. Handle Errors Accessibly

Error messages must be announced and clearly associated with their fields.

```csharp
public class AccessibleForm : ContentPage
{
    private Entry _emailEntry;
    private Label _emailError;

    private async Task ValidateAndSubmit()
    {
        if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(_emailEntry.Text))
        {
            // 1. Show visual error
            _emailError.Text = "Email is required";
            _emailError.IsVisible = true;
            _emailEntry.BorderColor = Colors.Red;

            // 2. Update accessibility state
            _emailEntry.SemanticProperties.Description = 
                "Email address. Error: Email is required";

            // 3. Announce error
            SemanticScreenReader.Announce("Email is required");

            // 4. Set focus to invalid field
            _emailEntry.Focus();

            return;
        }

        // Clear errors on success
        _emailError.IsVisible = false;
        _emailEntry.BorderColor = Colors.Gray;
        _emailEntry.SemanticProperties.Description = "Email address";
    }
}
```

## 9. Make Dynamic Content Accessible

Announce changes that occur without user interaction.

```csharp
public class NotificationBanner : ContentView
{
    public void ShowNotification(string message, NotificationType type)
    {
        // Update UI
        Content = new Frame
        {
            BackgroundColor = GetColorForType(type),
            Content = new Label { Text = message }
        };

        IsVisible = true;

        // Announce to screen reader
        var announcement = type switch
        {
            NotificationType.Error => $"Error: {message}",
            NotificationType.Warning => $"Warning: {message}",
            NotificationType.Success => $"Success: {message}",
            _ => message
        };

        SemanticScreenReader.Announce(announcement);

        // Auto-dismiss after delay
        Device.StartTimer(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5), () =>
        {
            IsVisible = false;
            SemanticScreenReader.Announce("Notification dismissed");
            return false;
        });
    }
}
```

## 10. Test with Real Assistive Technologies

Regularly test with Orca and other tools.

```csharp
// Unit test for accessibility
[Fact]
public void AllButtons_Should_Have_Accessible_Labels()
{
    var page = new MainPage();
    var buttons = GetAllDescendants<Button>(page);

    foreach (var button in buttons)
