## Visual Focus Indicators

Focused elements must be visually distinguishable:

```csharp
protected override void OnPaint(SKCanvas canvas)
{
    // Draw control content
    DrawContent(canvas);

    // Draw focus indicator
    if (IsFocused)
    {
        var focusRect = new SKRect(0, 0, Width, Height);
        focusRect.Inflate(-2, -2);

        using var paint = new SKPaint
        {
            Style = SKPaintStyle.Stroke,
            Color = SkiaTheme.Current.FocusColor,
            StrokeWidth = 2,
            PathEffect = SKPathEffect.CreateDash(new[] { 4f, 2f }, 0)
        };

        canvas.DrawRect(focusRect, paint);
    }
}
```

## Best Practices

1. **Make all interactive elements focusable**: Buttons, links, inputs, and custom controls should accept focus
2. **Provide visible focus indicators**: Users must see which element has focus
3. **Support standard shortcuts**: Ctrl+C/V/X for copy/paste/cut, Ctrl+A for select all, etc.
4. **Announce navigation changes**: Use `AnnounceAccessibility()` when focus moves or selection changes
5. **Test keyboard-only navigation**: Ensure your entire application is usable without a mouse
6. **Respect tab order**: Logical tab order follows visual layout (left-to-right, top-to-bottom)
7. **Trap focus in modals**: Dialogs should keep focus within themselves until closed

Proper keyboard navigation ensures that your application is fully accessible to users who rely on keyboard input, whether due to disability, preference, or workflow efficiency.

High contrast mode is essential for users with low vision or certain types of color blindness. Linux desktop environments provide system-wide high contrast themes, and applications must respect these settings to ensure readability and usability.

## Detecting High Contrast Mode

The OpenMaui platform integrates with the `SystemThemeService` to detect high contrast mode across different desktop environments:

```csharp
public class SystemThemeService
{
    private bool _isHighContrast;

    public bool IsHighContrastMode
    {
        get => _isHighContrast;
        private set
        {
            if (_isHighContrast != value)
            {
                _isHighContrast = value;
                OnHighContrastChanged();
            }
        }
    }

    public event EventHandler? HighContrastChanged;

    public void DetectHighContrast()
    {
        // GNOME detection
        if (IsGnomeDesktop())
        {
            var contrastSetting = GetGSettingsValue(
                "org.gnome.desktop.a11y.interface", 
                "high-contrast");
            IsHighContrastMode = contrastSetting == "true";
        }
        // KDE Plasma detection
        else if (IsKdeDesktop())
        {
            var theme = GetKdeColorScheme();
            IsHighContrastMode = theme.Contains("HighContrast", 
                StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase);
        }
        // Fallback: detect by theme name
        else
        {
            var themeName = GetGtkThemeName();
            IsHighContrastMode = themeName.Contains("HighContrast", 
                StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase);
        }
    }
}
```

## The SkiaTheme System

The `SkiaTheme` class provides centralized theme management with high contrast support:

```csharp
public class SkiaTheme
{
    public static SkiaTheme Current { get; private set; } = new();

    public bool IsDarkMode { get; set; }
    public bool IsHighContrast { get; set; }

    // Color properties with high contrast overrides
    public SKColor ForegroundColor => IsHighContrast 
        ? (IsDarkMode ? SKColors.White : SKColors.Black)
        : (IsDarkMode ? new SKColor(230, 230, 230) : new SKColor(30, 30, 30));

    public SKColor BackgroundColor => IsHighContrast
        ? (IsDarkMode ? SKColors.Black : SKColors.White)
        : (IsDarkMode ? new SKColor(30, 30, 30) : new SKColor(250, 250, 250));

    public SKColor AccentColor => IsHighContrast
        ? (IsDarkMode ? SKColors.Yellow : SKColors.Blue)
        : new SKColor(0, 120, 215); // Default blue

    public SKColor BorderColor => IsHighContrast
        ? ForegroundColor
        : (IsDarkMode ? new SKColor(60, 60, 60) : new SKColor(200, 200, 200));

    public SKColor FocusColor => IsHighContrast
        ? (IsDarkMode ? SKColors.Yellow : SKColors.Blue)
        : new SKColor(0, 120, 215);

    public SKColor DisabledForegroundColor => IsHighContrast
        ? (IsDarkMode ? new SKColor(128, 128, 128) : new SKColor(128, 128, 128))
        : (IsDarkMode ? new SKColor(100, 100, 100) : new SKColor(160, 160, 160));

    public float MinimumContrastRatio => IsHighContrast ? 7.0f : 4.5f;

    public static void ApplySystemTheme(bool isDark, bool isHighContrast)
    {
        Current = new SkiaTheme
        {
            IsDarkMode = isDark,
            IsHighContrast = isHighContrast
        };

        ThemeChanged?.Invoke(null, EventArgs.Empty);
    }

    public static event EventHandler? ThemeChanged;
}
```

## Applying High Contrast Themes to Controls

Controls automatically respond to theme changes:

```csharp
public class SkiaButton : SkiaView
{
    public SkiaButton()
    {
        SkiaTheme.ThemeChanged += OnThemeChanged;
    }

    private void OnThemeChanged(object? sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        InvalidateVisual(); // Trigger repaint with new colors
    }

    protected override void OnPaint(SKCanvas canvas)
    {
        var theme = SkiaTheme.Current;

        // Background
        var bgColor = IsEnabled 
            ? (IsPressed ? theme.AccentColor.WithAlpha(200) : theme.AccentColor)
            : theme.BackgroundColor;

        using (var paint = new SKPaint { Color = bgColor })
        {
            canvas.DrawRoundRect(Bounds, CornerRadius, CornerRadius, paint);
        }

        // Border (always visible in high contrast)
        if (theme.IsHighContrast || IsFocused)
        {
            using var borderPaint = new SKPaint
            {
                Style = SKPaintStyle.Stroke,
                Color = IsFocused ? theme.FocusColor : theme.BorderColor,
                StrokeWidth = theme.IsHighContrast ? 2 : 1
            };

            canvas.DrawRoundRect(Bounds, CornerRadius, CornerRadius, borderPaint);
        }

        // Text
        var textColor = IsEnabled 
            ? (theme.IsHighContrast ? theme.BackgroundColor : SKColors.White)
            : theme.DisabledForegroundColor;

        using (var textPaint = new SKPaint
        {
            Color = textColor,
            TextSize = FontSize,
            IsAntialias = true,
            Typeface = GetTypeface()
        })
        {
            canvas.DrawText(Text, TextX, TextY, textPaint);
        }
    }
}
```

## Ensuring Sufficient Contrast

The platform includes contrast checking utilities:

```csharp
public static class ContrastChecker
{
    public static double CalculateContrastRatio(SKColor foreground, SKColor background)
    {
        double luminance1 = GetRelativeLuminance(foreground);
        double luminance2 = GetRelativeLuminance(background);

        double lighter = Math.Max(luminance1, luminance2);
        double darker = Math.Min(luminance1, luminance2);

        return (lighter + 0.05) / (darker + 0.05);
    }

    private static double GetRelativeLuminance(SKColor color)
    {
        double r = GetLinearValue(color.Red / 255.0);
        double g = GetLinearValue(color.Green / 255.0);
        double b = GetLinearValue(color.Blue / 255.0);

        return 0.2126 * r + 0.7152 * g + 0.0722 * b;
    }

    private static double GetLinearValue(double value)
    {
        return value <= 0.03928 
            ? value / 12.92 
            : Math.Pow((value + 0.055) / 1.055, 2.4);
    }

    public static bool MeetsWCAGAA(SKColor foreground, SKColor background)
    {
        return CalculateContrastRatio(foreground, background) >= 4.5;
    }

    public static bool MeetsWCAGAAA(SKColor foreground, SKColor background)
    {
        return CalculateContrastRatio(foreground, background) >= 7.0;
    }
}
```

## High Contrast Best Practices for Custom Controls

When implementing custom controls:

```csharp
public class CustomControl : SkiaView
{
    protected override void OnPaint(SKCanvas canvas)
    {
        var theme = SkiaTheme.Current;

        // 1. Always draw borders in high contrast mode
        if (theme.IsHighContrast)
        {
            using var borderPaint = new SKPaint
            {
                Style = SKPaintStyle.Stroke,
                Color = theme.BorderColor,
                StrokeWidth = 2
            };
            canvas.DrawRect(Bounds, borderPaint);
        }

        // 2. Use solid colors, avoid gradients
        var fillColor = theme.IsHighContrast 
            ? theme.BackgroundColor 
            : GetGradientColor();

        // 3. Increase icon/text sizes slightly
        var fontSize = theme.IsHighContrast 
            ? FontSize * 1.1f 
            : FontSize;

        // 4. Remove transparency
        var color = theme.ForegroundColor;
        if (theme.IsHighContrast)
            color = color.WithAlpha(255);

        // 5. Use system colors, don't hardcode
        using var paint = new SKPaint
        {
            Color = theme.IsHighContrast 
                ? theme.ForegroundColor 
                : CustomColor
        };
    }
}
```

## Responding to Runtime Theme Changes

Users can toggle high contrast mode while your application is running:

```csharp
public class LinuxApplication
{
    private readonly SystemThemeService _themeService;

    public LinuxApplication()
    {
        _themeService = new SystemThemeService();
        _themeService.HighContrastChanged += OnHighContrastChanged;
        _themeService.StartMonitoring();
    }

    private void OnHighContrastChanged(object? sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Update global theme
        SkiaTheme.ApplySystemTheme(
            _themeService.IsDarkMode,
            _themeService.IsHighContrastMode);

        // All views automatically repaint due to ThemeChanged event

        // Announce to screen reader
        var mode = _themeService.IsHighContrastMode 
            ? "High contrast mode enabled" 
            : "High contrast mode disabled";
        AccessibilityManager.Announce(mode);
    }
}
```

